5	52	40ed233b-4c41-440e-9146-0560897ff56c	2	CSRF protection works by issuing a unique server-generated token stored in an HttpOnly cookie and requiring the client to include that token in each state-changing request so the server can verify the request’s legitimacy and block unauthorized cross-site actions.	7	Good	{"The user correctly identifies CSRF protection as involving server-generated tokens stored in HttpOnly cookies.","They mention that the client is required to include the token in each state-changing request."}	{"The user does not explicitly explain the importance of using HttpOnly cookies or how this helps prevent XSS attacks.","Their explanation does not delve deeply into the underlying security principles or common implementations beyond the basic concept."}	A strong answer would include a detailed explanation of the importance of using HttpOnly cookies to prevent XSS vulnerabilities and common implementations such as synchronizing the token using JavaScript or using a library/framework's CSRF protection features.	Focus on explaining the security principle behind using HttpOnly cookies and the importance of synchronizing the token on the client-side to enhance the answer's depth and practical relevance.	2026-05-05 23:06:38.475547
